ke.go.moh.oec.lib
Class XmlPacker

java.lang.Object
  ke.go.moh.oec.lib.XmlPacker

 class XmlPacker
extends java.lang.Object

Packs message data into XML strings, and unpacks XML strings into message data.

Note that all the methods in this class start with "pack", "unpack" or "common". "pack" methods are used only for packing XML messages. "unpack" methods are used only for unpacking XML messages. "common" methods are used by both.

Author:
Purity Chemutai, Jim Grace

packGenericPersonMessage

private org.w3c.dom.Document packGenericPersonMessage(Message m)
Packs a generic HL7 person-related message into a Document.

Several of the HL7 person-related messages use the same formatting rules, even though the templates differ. (The templates differ only in the boilerplate parts that do not concern us directly.) These messages are:

CREATE PERSON
MODIFY PERSON
NOTIFY PERSON CHANGED

Parameters:
m - notification message contents to pack
Returns:
packed notification messages

packPersonName

private void packPersonName(org.w3c.dom.Element e,
                            Person p,
                            java.lang.String tagName)
Packs a person's name. For findPerson the tagname containing the name elements is "livingSubjectName". For other person messages the tagName is "name".

The first and middle names are packed in two consecutive <given> nodes. The last name is packed in the <family> node. If none of the names are present, remove the whole <name> tag. Otherwise, remove the tag for any part of the name that is not present. The exception to this is if the first name is absent and the middle name is present, keep the first <given> node, but pack it with an empty string. That way the middle name will still go in the second <given> tag.

Parameters:
e - head of the Document subtree in which this person is to be packed
p - person data to pack into the subtree
tagName - name of the enclosing element for the person's name

packPersonIdentifiers

private void packPersonIdentifiers(org.w3c.dom.Element subtree,
                                   Person p,
                                   java.lang.String oidPersonIdentifier,
                                   PersonIdentifier.Type type)
Packs all person identifiers of a given type into a person subtree of a Document

Searches through all the identifiers for a person to find identifiers of the given type. The first such identifier replaces the template value. Subsequent identifiers are inserted into clones of the template value. If there is no identifier of the given type, the template value is removed.

Parameters:
subtree - head of the Document subtree in which this person is to be packed
p - person information containing the list of identifiers
oidPersonIdentifier - the XML template OID for this person identifier type
type - the person identifier type

packFingerprints

private void packFingerprints(org.w3c.dom.Element subtree,
                              Person p,
                              java.lang.String oidFingerprint,
                              Fingerprint.Type type)
Packs all fingerprints of a given type into a person subtree of a Document

Searches through through the person data for all fingerprints of the given type. The first such fingerprint replaces the template value. Subsequent fingerprints of the same type are inserted into clones of the template value. If there is no fingerprint of this type, the template for fingerprints of this type is removed.

Note that we don't really expect multiple fingerprints of the same type in the same message. But the list of fingerprints in the Person object allows for this possibility, as does the XML message template. So this method also allows for this possibility.

Parameters:
subtree - head of the Document subtree in which this person is to be packed
p - person information containing the list of identifiers
oidFingerprint - the XML template OID for this fingerprint type
type - the fingerprint type

packLivingSubjectAttribute

private void packLivingSubjectAttribute(org.w3c.dom.Element subtree,
                                        java.lang.String name,
                                        java.lang.String attribute,
                                        java.lang.String value)
Packs data into a named attribute of a livingSubject... construct.

This is used to pack data on behalf of findPerson into a subtree of the following form:

<livingSubjectXxx>
<value yyy=userValue>
<semanticsText>LivingSubject.xxx</semanticsText>
</livingSubjectXxx>

where livingSubjectXxx is the name of the top element in this subtree and yyy is the name of the attribute to receive the value.

Parameters:
subtree - Document subtree in which to look for the element
name - name of the element under which to pack the value
attribute - name of the element attribute to receive the value
value - value to place in the attribute. If null, the element is removed from the template.

packRemoveComments

private void packRemoveComments(org.w3c.dom.Node node)
Removes all comments from a document. (Used recursively, removes all comments below this element Node.)

The purpose of this method is so that XML comments may be used liberally within an XML template to document the expected values, and these comments may be removed before sending a protocol message using this template.

If a comment is on a line by itself, the line is also removed. More precisely, if a comment node is preceeded by a text node consisting of nothing but white space, the preceeding text node (as well as the comment) is removed. This effectively removes the whole line if the comment is on the line by itself. It also removes any white space before the comment if the comment is on the end of the line after other tags.

Parameters:
node - the Node below which we remove all comments.

packRemoveNode

private int packRemoveNode(org.w3c.dom.Node n)
Removes a node from the document node tree.

If the node is on a line by itself, the line is also removed. More precisely, if the node is preceeded by a text node consisting of nothing but white space, the preceeding text node (as well as the node) is removed. This effectively removes the whole line if the node is on the line by itself. It also removes any white space before the node if the node is on the end of the line after another node.

Parameters:
n -
Returns:
the number of nodes removed (1 if only the node was removed, 2 if a whitespace-only text node before it was also removed.) This may be useful to our caller if they are stepping through a list of nodes using an index. It tells them how many to subtract from the index to compensate for the deleted nodes and still properly evaluate all the nodes in the list.

Several of the HL7 person-related messages use the same formatting rules, even though the templates differ. (The templates differ only in the boilerplate parts that do not concern us directly.) These messages are:

unpackFingerprints

private void unpackFingerprints(Person p,
                                org.w3c.dom.Element e,
                                java.lang.String oidFingerprint,
                                Fingerprint.Type type)
Unpacks all ID-tagged fingerprints of a given type.

Searches through all the person identifiers in a Document subtree to find identifiers of the given type. For each such identifier, allocates a PersonIdentifier object and attaches it to the Person object.

Note that we don't really expect multiple fingerprints of the same type in the same message. But the list of fingerprints in the Person object allows for this possibility, as does the XML message template. So this method also allows for this possibility.

Parameters:
p - person information
e - head of the Document subtree in which these fingerprints are to be found
oidFingerprint - the XML template OID for this fingerprint type
type - fingerprint type
